Exploring the Visual Nature of London Urban Development with Convolutional Neural Networks¶

  • Companion Python Code for Dissertation Submission (MRes in Spatial Data Science and Visualisation - Bartlett UCL 2017)
  • Presentation version of the Jupyter Script Workflows (inc Explanatory notes, Screenshots and Clipped Cell Output for notebook size reduction)
  • Raw Code is available in a seperate folder

Workflow 1 - Data Model Build and Exploration¶

Aim¶

  • Setting the Scene - What Does New London Look Like?
  • Introducing Research Themes: Visualising Urban Change with Aggregate Real Time London Visual Building Data > Using Machine Learning to understand macro level phenomena> Public Enfranchisement > Digital Property Cadastre
  • Introducing the Datasets(OS AddressBase, OpenStreetMap, GLA's London Development Database)
  • Exploring Potential Data Models
  • Augmenting our Data Model with Auxiliary Investigative Threads (CACI Acorn GeoDemographic Classes, London Ward and Borough Census, MIT Place Pulse Crowdsource Project(Cognitive/Psychological), TFL PTAL Zones, Town Planning Use Classes, New London vs Old London)
  • Quick Spin Tensorflow CNN Trainer for Identifying Suitable Candidate Image Datasets for CNN Image Classification Task
  • Additional Holoviz, DataShader and Processing 3 Data Model Exploration
  • Building the Final Data Model

Method¶

## Table Plotting Functions
def plotdat(data,cat):
    #Set Min Number of Records   
    data = data.groupby('ClassificationCode').filter(lambda x : len(x)>5)
    l=data.groupby(cat).size()
    l.sort_values()
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))
    plt.yticks(fontsize=8)
    l.plot(kind='bar',fontsize=12,color='k')  
    plt.xlabel('',)
    plt.ylabel('Number of ...',fontsize=10)
    plt.show()

## Table Label Helper
def printmd(string):
    display(Markdown(string))

  • Intro to CNN Training Label Requirements and OSM Fuzzy Chalenges for Script 4/3

Address Base Schema¶
  • Split into Code, Description
  • Use Class orientated schema
  • Urban Design: Physical Function vs Physical Form
  • Challenges for a CNN Classification Task
  • Hierachical Scale: Primary, Secondary, Tertiary, Quaternary classes of address descritptor
  • Introduction of Crisp and Fuzzy set matching and membership

def plotdat_label(data,cat):
    #We need al least 100 Images for the CNN
    data = data.groupby('ClassificationCode').filter(lambda x : len(x)>100)
    l=data.groupby(cat).size()
    l.sort_values()
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(20,5))
    plt.yticks(fontsize=8)
    l.plot(kind='bar',fontsize=12,color='k')  
    plt.xlabel('Property Type',)
    plt.ylabel('Number of ...',fontsize=10)
    plt.show()

Comments¶
  • Greater spread of Address Class Examples on London Wide Scale
  • We have included a minimum record filter(n >=100)which is the recomended number of training data per class for the ImageNet CNN Architecture
  • Compare Local Pattern against London Wide average:
    • Most Adddresses fall into these codes (in descending order of data sample size) -
      • Residential:
        • Flat
        • Detached
        • Semi-Detached
        • Terrace
      • Commerical:
        • Retail
        • Office
        • Industrial (very small)
  • Significant number of addresses in non misc categories (Address Container, Generic Class(e.g. Residential, Commericial)
    • Indicates the challenges of describing/classifying Living Urban Spaces that are in Henri Levebre's 'continual state of production'.
  • To Do: London Wide Pattern vs UK Wide vs Europe vs Global?

def types_districts(area,per):
    
    # Group by  type and district 
    area_per_type=area.groupby('ClassificationCode').Planning_A.value_counts(sort=True)
    t=area_per_type.unstack().fillna(0)
    
    # Sort by boro sum
    area_sum=t.sum(axis=0)
    area_sum.sort_index(ascending=False)
    t=t[area_sum.index]
    
    # Filter by count per district
    area_sum=t.sum(axis=1)
    area_sum.sort_index()
    
    # Large number, so let's slice the data.
    p=np.percentile(area_sum,per)
    ix=area_sum[area_sum>p]
    t=t.loc[ix.index]
    return t
    
t=types_districts(df_ldd_acorn_dates_join,96)
